reviews.review_text:
Upgrade!!! Providence 1985 - Beware of Splice in She Belongs To Me Thank you Charlie Miller and Scott Clugston for the transfer & mastering of this sweet UPGRADE! Also big thanks to Matthew Vernon for the uploads! Without a doubt one of my all time favorites from 1985. As for this show, I’ve been waiting for an upgrade since I first heard it in 1985. And after downloading the sweet new Rob Hunt & Ted Mattes Audience shnid=149316 on it’s 35th anniversary (a day ago), I thought to myself boy I wish we could get an upgrade of that SBD. Must be some of that good ole Grateful Dead serendipity cause here it is! 

ABOUT THE TAPE:
Listening to this source it appears that this is the same SBD source as the unknown shnid=126237 that has been on Archive.org since 2013, but with a much better transfer and some nice mastering (I could be wrong, but again that’s what it sounds like). Unfortunately, there’s still one issue that might’ve been missed / overlooked. Please note, this is not a complaint, I’m just mentioning it for other collector Heads in hopes of a remedy. Per the notes of the 2013 SBD shnid=126237 the following is stated, and still remains true on this 2020 upgrade (shnid=149449): “there is a very unfortunate cut in She Belongs to Me at 4:06.56, which lasted for 5.48 seconds.  It appears that someone forgot to "pop the top" off their cassette, so I suspect it's not present on the master (wherever that might be)”. I can confirm that this unfortunate splice is sadly still present in “She Belongs to Me” on this upgrade at appx 4:10. However, there is patch material for it. SBD shnid=11704 from 2004 does not have this splice and makes for a good patch source. I patched mine with it and it works pretty nicely with some minor adjustments. The Oade audience might work for it as well. I just wanted to let you all know.  This “She Belongs To Me” is my favorite version of all time and I’d hoped the issue wouldn’t be present, cause a splice in such a sweet rendition is really unbearable, but thanks to technology it’s fixable. Just a heads up to the Heads! 


SHOW REVIEW:
This is definitely a superb Set 1, I love it and would highly recommend it to anybody that loves ’85 GD. Here’s my story on this tape. Shortly after these shows happened in 1985 my good friend’s Older Brother & his best friend who were two years older than us (High School Juniors we were Freshman) had just come back from spring tour and dropped by my place with some party favors they’d returned with.  We all headed down to my basement room between classes, and I figured I’d try and impress them with my musical knowledge. So I popped in my newly acquired favorite GD tape at the time WALSTIB (Warner Bros best of collection) and cranked it up.  They looked at each other and were like, what’s with this old shit? The best friend gets up and ejected that tape with some obvious disdain and punched this tape in for us to dig. That’s when the light bulb went on for me. By Jack Straw (I didn’t know Alabama Getaway yet) I asked them,  “Wait a minute, this sounds way different?”. They were like yeah, well Pigpen’s not around anymore and Brent’s with the band and this is how they sound now, this is from one of the shows we just saw on tour. Fifteen year old mind blown, I asked “These guys are still playing? You just saw them? And you have a tape of the show you just saw?” That was it, I had to know more about this band, the bus came by and I got on… and the trip began and I’m still tripping 35 years later:) As for the show, it’s another of those magic GD things, if I based it completely on the song list, I’d never have picked this as a favorite, there’s no Playing In The Band, The Other One, Scarlet > Fire, none of that stuff, but I love this tape! Set 1 is amazing with a ripping Alabama opener, great great versions of Jack Straw, Dire Wolf > El Paso > She Belongs To Me, that’s money right there, one of my favorite versions of Brother Esau which goes into > FOTD followed by some L > S > D! Set 2 again I’d never pick this set list as a future favorite, but it’s well executed and inspired at times, Crazy Fingers & the pre-Drums GDTRFB followed by a sick jam where it sounds like they might be thinking Cumberland, I almost hear some Caution in there > Drums > Space (now patched very nicely after 35 years) > The Wheel > Black Peter > Around > Lovelight, what’s not to like? You can just hear that the boys are having fun, and when the boys were having fun, we all had / have fun. The personal connection of this being my first exposure to 1985 Dead back in ’85 and that it’s the tape that flipped my switch and all I can say is this one makes me happy. And what’s wrong with a little joy? Lord knows we can use that in the world today. This brought some to me, I hope it brings some to you. Listen and see. 

Alright, hope this helps someone on their collecting journey and again my hat is off to Charlie, Scott, Matt and crew!! Keep up the good work, I can’t tell you how much I am LOVING what you all do, you’re my GD heroes!

PS - I hate having to rate things and this rating does not reflect on any of the hard work and efforts of so many. I give the show 5 stars. The upgrade gets 4 stars, it woulda got 5 without the splice (again not complaining, just saying). Cool thing is with that one star missing we can keep hoping for a 5 star version some day. Keep the Hope people!
